# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-alarm-control-panel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A **fire alarm control panel** (**FACP**), **fire alarm control unit** (**FACU**), **fire indicator panel** (**FIP**), or simply **fire alarm panel** is the controlling component of a fire alarm system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The panel receives information from devices designed to detect and report fires, monitors their operational integrity, and provides for automatic control of equipment, and transmission of information necessary to prepare the facility for fire based on a predetermined sequence.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The panel may also supply electrical energy to operate any associated initiating device, notification appliance, control, transmitter, or relay.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] There are four basic types of panels: coded panels, conventional panels, addressable panels, and multiplex systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Coded panels were the earliest type of central fire alarm control, and were made during the 1800s to the 1970s.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Large panels could take up an entire wall in a mechanical room, with dozens of code wheels.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Lists of codes had to be maintained, sometimes with copies posted above pull stations (this setup is commonly seen in older wings of hospitals).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Smaller panels could be set up in one of two ways.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Most of the time, the panel would only have one zone, and therefore, only one code.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Alternatively, the panel could be made with no code wheels, using only what was called the gong relay.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Normally, this would be used in a system with coded pull stations to re-transmit the coding strikes from the pulls.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] However, it could also be used as its own zone, with the connected horns or bells sounding continuously instead of in a particular code.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] These panels are not common today, but can sometimes be found in older buildings such as those on college campuses or hospitals.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Classic electromechanical coded panels using relays and coded interruptor wheels are functionally obsolete, and have been largely replaced.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] "Conventional" panels have been around ever since electronic components became small enough to make them viable replacements for the historic electromechanical control panels.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Conventional panels are used less frequently in large buildings than in the past, but are still seen on smaller projects such as small schools, stores, restaurants, and apartment buildings.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A conventional fire alarm control panel employs one or more electrical signalling circuits (each a pair of wires), connected to initiating devices (usually smoke detectors, heat detectors, duct detectors, manual pull stations, and sometimes flame detectors) wired in parallel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] These sensors are designed to dramatically decrease the circuit resistance (a "closed" state) when the environmental conditions on any sensor exceed a predetermined trigger threshold.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In a conventional fire alarm system, the information density or resolution is limited to the number of such individual wired circuits installed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] To facilitate location and control of fire within a building, the structure usually is subdivided into distinct identified areas or zones.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Floors of a multi-storey building are one type of zone boundary.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A very simple system may have a small number of zones.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] An Initiating Device Circuit (known as a Signalling Line Circuit (SLC) in addressable systems) connected to multiple devices within the same "zone" of protection, effectively provides 3 distinct states of information about the zone to the panel: Normal, Trouble, or Alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The state of each initiating device circuit within a zone displays at the fire alarm control panel using visible indications, such as a flashing LED/light or an LCD.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The panel may employ a graphical representation of the zone boundaries on a floor plan (zone map) using textual descriptions, illuminated icons, illuminated sections, or illuminated points on the map corresponding to initiating circuits connected to the fire alarm control panel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Annunciators that display this way are called graphic annunciators.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] An important output of any alarm control panel is the Notification Appliance Circuit (NAC).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This signal triggers alarm horns, strobe lights, and whatever other notification appliances are used to alert building occupants of an alarm condition.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This arrangement forms a device-type-by-zone matrix whose information is particularly suited to a tabular annunciator.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In multistorey buildings employing a tabular annunciator, for example: rows of indicators define the floors horizontally in their stacked relationship and the type of device installed on that floor displays as columns of indicators vertically aligned through each floor.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The intersection of the floor and device indicators provides the combined information.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The density of information however remains a function of the number of circuits employed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Even larger systems and demands for finer diagnostic and location detail led to the introduction of addressable fire alarm systems, with each addressable device providing specific information about its state while sharing a common communication circuit.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Annunciation and location strategies for the most part remain relatively unchanged.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Multiplex systems, a sort of transition between conventional and modern addressable systems, were often used in large buildings and complexes from the mid to late 1970s into the late 1980s.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Early on, these systems were programmed to function as large conventional systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Gradually, later installations began to feature components and features of modern addressable systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] These systems were often capable of controlling more than a building's fire alarm system (i.e.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] HVAC, security, electronic door locks, etc.) without any type of alarm or trouble condition present.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] While the main panel was the brains of the system and could be used to access certain functions, fire alarm controls were usually accessed through transponders.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] These were smaller conventional panels programmed to "communicate" the status of part of the system to the main panel, and which also could be used to access basic fire alarm control functions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Addressable panels are usually more advanced than their conventional counterparts, with much greater information capacity and control flexibility.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Addressable fire alarm panels were introduced by many manufacturers during the microcontroller boom in the mid 1980s.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Addressable Fire Alarm Control Panel employ one or more Signalling Line Circuits - usually referred to as **loop**s or **SLC loop**s - ranging between one and thirty.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Depending on the protocol used, a Signaling Line Circuit can monitor and control up to several hundred devices.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Some protocols permit any mix of detectors and input/output modules, while other protocols have 50% of channel capacity restricted to detectors/sensors and 50% restricted to input/output modules.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Each SLC polls the devices connected, which can number from a few devices to several hundred, depending on the manufacturer.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Large systems may have multiple Signalling Line Circuits.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Each device on an SLC has its own unique address, and thus the panel knows the state of each individual device connected to it.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Also known as "cause and effect", mapping is the process of activating outputs depending on which inputs have been activated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Traditionally, when an input device is activated, a certain output device (or relay) is activated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] As time has progressed, more and more advanced techniques have become available, often with large variations in style between different companies.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Zones are usually made by dividing a building or area into different sections.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Then depending on the specific zone, a certain number and type of device is added to the zone to perform its given job.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Zones are a requirement of the National Building Code in Canada, and zones must be labelled and include red LEDs for fire zones, with amber LEDs for supervisory and trouble.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The LED indicators are in addition to an LCD, although this requirement is waived if the LCD has 8 or more lines of characters.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Isolators are also required when wiring departs a zone and enters a new zone such as floor to floor and between firewalls.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Groups contain multiple output devices such as relays.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This allows a single input, such as a smoke detector or alarm pull station to have only one output programmed to a group, which then maps to multiple outputs or relays.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This enables an installer to simplify programming by having many inputs map to the same outputs, and be able to change them all at once, and also allows mapping to more outputs than the programming space for a single detector/input allows.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This is the part of a fire panel that may have the largest variation between different panels.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This capability allows a panel to be programmed to detect fairly complex inputs.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] For instance, a panel could be programmed to notify the fire department only if more than one device has activated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] It can also be used for staged evacuation procedures in conjunction with timers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The principle of networking involves connecting several panels together to form an integrated system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Inputs on one panel may activate outputs on another for example, or the network may allow monitoring of many systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Networking is often used in situations where one panel is not large enough, or in multiple-building situations.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Networking is also an effective way to decouple systems to reduce the risk of a large portion of a facility going offline at any time due to system failure or maintenance requirements.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Sub-networks can be created using either hardware or software architectures.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Networked systems normally are more costly and involve additional training and system configuration for successful implementation.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Although quasi-standards exist allowing panels from different manufacturers to be networked with each other, they are not always supported by all companies.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] One of the most common protocols used is BACnet, which is already common for various type of industrial networks.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Typical interconnected systems to the Fire Alarm Control Panel include HVAC, Building Automation Controllers, Security/Access Control, or Elevator Controllers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The Arcnet protocol has been used for years in industrial applications, and is also used for networking Fire Alarm Control Panels.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] More recently, some panels are being networked with standard Ethernet, but this is not yet very common.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Many organizations choose to create their own proprietary protocol, which has the added benefit of allowing them to do anything they like, allowing the technology to progress further.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] However, a bridging layer between the proprietary network and BACnet is usually available.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Networking may be used to allow a number of different panels to be monitored by one centralized graphical monitoring system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Releasing panels are capable of using solenoids to disperse fire-fighting chemical agents such as Halon or water from piping located throughout a building.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A releasing panel usually will have a manual abort switch to abort an accidental release which could damage property or equipment.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Releasing capability can be part of both addressable or conventional panels.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Other types of fire alarm control panels include voice evacuation panels, which are panels designed to provide outputs for speakers in the system when the main panel does not already have built-in voice evacuation ability.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Another type are Notification Appliance Circuit (NAC) extenders (also called power supplies) usually meant for powering more notification appliances than the main panel could normally power, though sometimes NAC extenders are also used for synchronization of the alarms.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In nearly every state in the US, the International Building Code requires fire alarm and sprinkler systems to be monitored by an approved supervising station.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A fire alarm system consists of a computer-based control connected to a central station.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The majority of fire alarm systems installed in the US are monitored by a UL listed or FM Global approved supervising station.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] These systems will generally have a top level map of the entire site, with various building levels displayed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The user (most likely a security guard) can progress through the different stages.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] From top level site → building plan → floor plan → zone plan, or however else the building's security system is organized.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Many of these systems have touch screens, but most users tend to prefer a mouse (and a normal monitor), as it is quite easy for a touch screen to become misaligned and for mistakes to be made.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] With the advent of the optical mouse, this is now a very viable option.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] There are many control functions on a fire alarm panel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This resets the panel after an alarm condition.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] All initiating devices are reset, (except for pull stations which must be reset manually) and the panel is cleared of any alarm conditions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A system reset is often required to clear supervisory conditions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A system reset does not usually clear trouble conditions; most trouble conditions will clear automatically when conditions are returned to normal.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This function (also abbreviated as "ACK") is used to manually acknowledge an abnormal situation such as an alarm, trouble, or supervisory signal.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This usually stops the panel "piezo" from sounding, and makes the activated (flashing) LED turn on steady ("go solid").
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This also cancels the auto-evacuation timer (3–5 minutes depending on occupancy type) from advancing from first stage to second stage evacuation.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Signal silence allows for easier verbal communication amongst emergency responders while responding to an alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This can also be used during building construction as a method of preliminary test, before the final full system test.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Signal silence is usually used right after the emergency has been dealt with, and the building is ready to be reoccupied again.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A system reset usually is done soon after.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This button (also known as "flash test") is still used on many panels to check the condition of the indicator lights (LEDs) themselves.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A "Lamp Test" button is required by code on multi-zone panels installed in Canada.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Many panels also do an automatic lamp test when the system is reset.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A "walk test" is a method of testing many fire alarm devices in a system, which saves time and requires fewer technicians at the location.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Using "walk test", a single technician can simply walk around the building and activate any device they would like.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Doing so will send a signal to the panel, which will either pulse the Notification Appliance Circuit (NAC) a certain number of times to indicate the zone on which the device is wired to, or simply sound the notification appliances for a few seconds, then automatically reset.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A "silent walk test" will only flash the alarm light on the panel, thus not sounding the signals.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] On panels that have this function, the drill function (also known as "manual evacuation") activates the system's notification appliances (NAC), often for purposes of conducting a fire drill.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Using the drill function, a remote alarm is normally not transmitted to the fire department or monitoring center, as the auxiliary relays for this function are not activated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] However, building personnel often notify these agencies in advance anyway, in case an alarm is inadvertently transmitted.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This button, or input terminals connected to an external timer switch, will sound the notification appliances briefly in a different cadence from the fire alarm sequence.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] It is used to signify class change or lesson breaks in schools, and allows the fire alarm system to be used instead of a separate class bell system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This ensures pupils are familiar with the sound of the alarm, and means the notification appliance circuits are tested several times a day.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Many panels today have the capability of alerting building personnel of a situation which could develop into a potentially serious problem.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Fire alarm panels indicate an abnormal condition via a solid or flashing LED.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Most panels also contain a small sounder, called a "piezo", used in conjunction with the visual alert.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A number of indicators are described below, but not all fire alarm panels have all of these indicators.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Also known as "Fire" or "General Alarm".
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This indicator is lit when an alarm condition exists in the system, initiated by smoke detectors, heat detectors, sprinkler flow switches, manual pull stations, manual call points, or otherwise.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Along with the indicator on the panel, notification appliances, such as horns and strobes, are also activated via the Notification Appliance Circuit (NAC), signalling to building occupants that they must evacuate.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In an alarm condition, the fire alarm panel indicates where the alarm originated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The alarm panel can be reset once the device which initiated the alarm has been reset, such as returning the handle of a manual pull station to its normal position.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Also known as "Signals Silenced" or "Alarm Silenced", this indicator is used in conjunction with the "Alarm" indicator.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] It indicates that the fire alarm panel is still in an alarm condition, but that notification appliances (NACs) have been silenced.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] While the alarm is silenced, other functions in an alarm condition continue to operate, such as emergency service for elevators, stairway pressurization, and ventilation functions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] A new alarm initiation signal while the alarm is silenced will take the panel out of Silence and reactivate the notification appliances.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Also known as "Manual Evacuation" or "Evacuate".
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] On panels containing this function, the "Drill" indicator shows that the alarm condition was activated from the fire alarm panel, often in order to conduct a fire drill.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] When an alarm is initiated for a drill, the fire department or monitoring company is usually not notified automatically.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This LED is often used in conjunction with a two-stage system, in which the panel requires two devices to be activated (and/or a predetermined time limit to run out after one device is activated) in order to go into full alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This is mostly used in areas where false alarms are a common problem, or in large applications (such as hospitals) where evacuating the entire building would not be efficient.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The pre-alarm LED is lit when one device has tripped.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] The pre-alarm LED may also be used if an addressable smoke detector registers low levels of smoke in the detection chamber, but not enough to trigger a full alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Depending on the system's layout, the Notification Appliance Circuit (NAC) may or may not activate for pre-alarm conditions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In a two-stage system, the NACs are typically coded to a special first-stage coding, or in some situations where a loud alarm signal could be disruptive, chimes will activate.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] If there is a voice evacuation system, it will usually instruct building occupants to await further instructions while the alarm is being investigated.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] When held steady or flashing, it means that a trouble condition exists on the panel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Trouble conditions are often activated by a contaminated smoke detector or an electrical problem within the system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Trouble conditions are also activated by a zone being disabled, a circuit or NAC being disabled, low power on the backup battery, disabling of a notification appliance, ground faults, or short or open circuits.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Usually the alarm panel's sounder will activate if a trouble condition exists, though older systems would sometimes activate a bell or other audible signal connected to the panel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] In a trouble condition, the panel displays the zone or devices causing the condition.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Usually, the "Trouble" indicator goes out automatically when the situation causing the trouble condition is rectified; however in some systems the panel must be manually reset to clear the trouble alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Some panels have more specific indicators such as "Trouble-PSU" which shows when the panel itself is compromised, and "Trouble-Bell" or "NAC Trouble" ("Sounder Fault" on UK panels) which shows that the notification appliances are not functioning or connected correctly.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] On most panels, an acknowledge button is pressed to turn off the panel's sounder.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] Depending on the system's design, the supervisory point may be latching, meaning the panel must be reset to clear the supervisory condition, or non-latching, meaning the indicator automatically goes out when the condition has cleared.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] However, some panels require a manual reset regardless of whether the supervisory point is latching or non-latching.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] When this (usually green) indicator is lit, power is being provided to the system from the building's electrical system, and not from the backup battery.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] When an AC power condition changes, the Trouble indicator comes on and the AC power indicator either goes off or starts flashing, and the panel alerts building personnel of a power failure.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] If the AC power indicator is lit without any other indicators also lit, then the system is in a normal non-alarm condition.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] If no LEDs are lit, there is no power source feeding the panel.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This is used to tell the operator that the panel's DC power (batteries) is being charged or used.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] While relying on DC backup power, the system remains in a fault condition.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/addressable-fire-alarm-systems] This LED is on when the battery charger is in the high rate charge state, in which the charger voltage is boosted to charge batteries faster after they have been depleted.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] An **alarm monitoring center**, **central monitoring station** (also known as "CMS" or wholesale central station), or **alarm receiving center** (also known as **ARC**) is a company that provides services to monitor burglar, fire, and residential alarm systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] The Central Monitoring Station may also provide watchman and supervisory services.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Central monitoring stations use special telephone and mobile lines, radio channels, computers, software and trained staff to monitor their customers' security systems and call the appropriate authorities in the event an alarm signal is received.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Typically, there is a monthly fee for services rendered.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Because quality and experience can vary greatly among alarm companies, prospective customers are well advised to do their own research before making a final choice.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Not all alarm companies monitor the systems they install and may outsource these services to another company.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Some facilities are certified by independent agencies.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] In the US, Underwriters Laboratories (UL) is a leader in inspection and certification of central-stations.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] UL Standard 827 must be adhered to in order to maintain a UL issued central-station listing.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] UL conducts annual audits of these listed facilities to ensure compliance.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] "UL listed" companies typically offer higher levels of service and reliability because they are mandated to follow certain regulations.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Higher levels of service also include range of services, and a separation from companies with conflicts of interest who may be owned or operated by entities that in fact compete with the central station's customers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] If the UL listed central station is "automated", the computers and software must meet special requirements, processing and storing very large amounts of data and integration with many different alarm protocols.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] In addition, many central monitoring stations seek to become FM approved in order to demonstrate additional levels of regulation compliance and interest for customer safety.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Incoming signals are processed by digital alarm receivers; these convert the incoming event packets to serial or TCP packets which are then analysed by the Central Station software.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Event packets can be communicated over any transmission medium: PSTN, GSM, radio, direct line, Ethernet, GPRS, etc.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] In the United States, central stations are regulated by third-party inspection companies such as Underwriters Laboratories (UL), FM Approvals, and The Monitoring Association (TMA).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Central stations are evaluated on specific criteria such as system redundancy, building security, and regulation compliance.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Once a central station has demonstrated adherence to the UL requirements, it can receive its certification.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Incorporated in 1950, TMA is legally entitled to represent its members before Congress and regulatory agencies on the local, state and federal levels, and other authorities having jurisdiction (AHJs) over the industry.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] The Monitoring Association also inspects and certifies central stations.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] In Australia, central stations are graded against Australian Standard 2201.2 which addresses both physical construction and operational performance.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Physical performance is graded A, B or C (where A is the highest grading) and includes measures such as the construction of monitoring rooms – higher security monitoring centres have solid concrete and steel construction with mantraps for access that can only be operated internally.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Operational performance is graded 1, 2 or 3 (with one being the highest grading).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] It includes the ability of the monitoring centre to respond to events – generated by customers' security systems, operational reliability, data retrieval, etc.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Accordingly, the highest grading is A1 and the lowest is C3 however even to be graded at C3 central stations still meet very high standards.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] There is presently no legislative imperative for an Australian central station to be 'graded' however police may refuse to respond to alarms despatched by non-graded companies and insurers may also deny a claim where an insured customer's system was monitored by an ungraded provider.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] The Australian Security Industry Association Limited (ASIAL) runs a grading scheme and publishes a list of graded monitoring centres.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] In the UK a similar structure of auditing takes place, with the National Approval Council for Security Systems provision of inspection and certification.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Numerous standards such as BS5979 must be adhered to in order for a central station to be allowed to pass alerts to the police force.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/alarm-monitoring-center] Emerging European standards are superseding these at this time.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET was developed by principal development engineer John Murphy, at Datapoint Corporation in 1976 under Victor Poor, and announced in 1977.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] It was originally developed to connect groups of their Datapoint 2200 terminals to talk to a shared 8" floppy disk system.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] It was the first loosely coupled LAN-based clustering system, making no assumptions about the *type* of computers that would be connected.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This was in contrast to contemporary larger and more expensive computer systems such as DECnet or IBM's SNA, where a homogeneous group of similar or proprietary computers were connected as a cluster.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] The token-passing bus protocol of that I/O device-sharing network was subsequently applied to allowing processing nodes to communicate with each other for file-serving and computing scalability purposes.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] An application could be developed in DATABUS, Datapoint's proprietary COBOL-like language, and deployed on a single computer with dumb terminals.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] When the number of users outgrew the capacity of the original computer, additional 'compute' resource computers could be attached via ARCNET to run the same applications and access the same data.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] If more storage was needed, additional disk resource computers could also be attached.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This incremental approach broke new ground and by the end of the 1970s (before the first IBM PC was announced in 1981), over ten thousand ARCNET LAN installations were in commercial use around the world while Datapoint had become a Fortune 500 company.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] As microcomputers took over the industry, well-proven and reliable ARCNET was also offered as an inexpensive LAN for these machines.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET remained proprietary until the early-to-mid 1980s.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This did not cause concern at the time, as most network architectures were proprietary.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] The move to non-proprietary, open systems began as a response to the dominance of International Business Machines (IBM) and its Systems Network Architecture (SNA).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In 1979, the Open Systems Interconnection Reference Model (OSI model) was published.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Then, in 1980, Digital, Intel and Xerox (the DIX consortium) published an open standard for Ethernet that was soon adopted as the basis of standardization by the IEEE and the ISO.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] IBM responded by proposing Token Ring as an alternative to Ethernet but kept such tight control over standardization that competitors were wary of using it.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET was less expensive than either of these, was more reliable, more flexible and, by the late 1980s, had a market share about equal to that of Ethernet.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Tandy/Radio Shack offered ARCNET as an application and file sharing medium for their TRS-80 Model II, Model 12, Model 16, Tandy 6000, Tandy 2000, Tandy 1000 and Tandy 1200 computer models.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] There were also hooks in the Model 4P's ROM to boot from an ARCNET network.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Ethernet became much more attractive when it moved from co-axial cable to twisted pair and an "interconnected stars" cabling topology based on active hubs.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Easier cabling, combined with the greater raw speed of Ethernet (10 Mbit/s versus 2.5 Mbit/s for ARCnet) helped to increase Ethernet's demand.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] As more companies entered the market, the price of Ethernet started to fall while ARCNET and Token Ring volumes tapered off.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In response to greater bandwidth needs, and the challenge of Ethernet, a new standard called ARCnet Plus was developed by Datapoint and introduced in 1992.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCnet Plus ran at 20 Mbit/s and was backward-compatible with original ARCnet equipment.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] However, by the time ARCnet Plus products were ready for the market, Ethernet had captured the majority of the network market and there was little incentive for users to move back to ARCnet.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] As a result, very few ARCnet Plus products were ever produced.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Those that were built, mainly by Datapoint, were expensive and hard to find.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET was eventually standardized as ANSI ARCNET 878.1.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] It appears this was when the name changed from ARCnet to ARCNET.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Other companies entered the market, notably Standard Microsystems who produced systems based on a single VLSI chip, originally developed as custom LSI for Datapoint, but later made available by Standard Microsystems to other customers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Datapoint eventually found itself in financial trouble and moved into video conferencing then and later to custom programming in the embedded market.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Even though ARCNET is now rarely used for new general networks, the diminishing installed base still requires support and it retains a niche in industrial control.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Original ARCNET used RG-62/U coaxial cable of 93 Ω impedance and either passive or active hubs in a star-wired bus topology.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] At the time of its greatest popularity, this was a significant advantage of ARCNET over thin Ethernet (10BASE2).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] A star-wired topology was easier to build, expand and service than the linear Ethernet bus of the time.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] The "interconnected stars" cabling topology made it easy to add and remove nodes without taking down the whole network, and much easier to diagnose and isolate failures within a complex LAN.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Another significant advantage ARCNET had over Ethernet was cable distance.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET coax cable runs could extend 610 m (2,000 ft) between active hubs or between an active hub and an end node, while the RG-58 (50 Ω) thin Ethernet was limited to a maximum run of 185 m (607 ft) from end to end.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET had the disadvantage of requiring either an active or passive hub between nodes if there were more than two nodes in the network, while Ethernet allowed nodes to be placed anywhere along the linear coax cable.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] However, ARCNET passive hubs were very inexpensive, being composed of a simple, small, unpowered box with four BNC ports, wired together with just a star of four 47 Ω resistors, so the disadvantage was not significant.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This disadvantage can also be seen as an advantage: often the cost of a 4 port ARCNET passive hub was less than the 4 BNC Tee connectors and 2 terminators that thin Ethernet requires to connect 4 computers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Unlike BNC Tee connectors that could sometimes be hard to obtain in the early days of Ethernet, an ARCNET passive hub could be easily manufactured in the field with 9 readily available parts: 4 connectors, 4 resistors and a box to put them in.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Passive hubs limited the distance between a node and an active hub to 30 m (100 ft).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] A passive hub could not be connected directly to another passive hub.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Unused ports on both types of hubs had to be terminated with a special connector.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This special connector, called a terminator, is just a BNC connector with a 93 Ω resistor in it.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Thin Ethernet also requires nearly identical terminators at the two terminal ends, the only difference being Ethernet uses a 50 Ω resistor.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] To reduce costs while still allowing wide area coverage, a common practice was to use one or more interconnected active hubs, each of which provided coverage for nodes no more than 60 m (200 ft) away.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Cable was run from each port of the active hubs to a different location no more than 30 m (100 ft) away.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] A passive hub would then be attached to the end of the cable, and cables would be run locally from the passive hub, allowing connection of up to three nodes.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In this way, a single 8-port active hub could be used to connect 24 networked devices over an area not exceeding 120 m (400 ft) in diameter.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET allowed only 255 nodes per network.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Node IDs for LAN workstations were typically set by DIP switches on the network interface card.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Larger networks would have to be split into smaller networks, and bridged.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] The small number of possible nodes and the need to manually configure IDs was a disadvantage compared with Ethernet, particularly as large enterprise networks became common.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] To mediate access to the bus, ARCNET, like Token Ring, uses a token passing scheme, rather than the carrier sense multiple access approach of Ethernet.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] When peers are inactive, a single "token" message is passed around the network from machine to machine and no peer is allowed to use the bus unless it has the token.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] If a particular peer wishes to send a message, it waits to receive the token, sends its message then passes the token on to the next station.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Because ARCNET is implemented as a distributed star, the token cannot be passed machine to machine around a ring.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Instead, each node is assigned an 8 bit address (usually via DIP switches), and when a new node joins the network a "reconfig" occurs, wherein each node learns the address of the node immediately above it.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] The token is then passed directly from one node to the next.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET had slightly lower best-case performance (viewed by a single stream), but was much more predictable.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET also has the advantage that it achieved its best aggregate performance under the highest loading, approaching asymptotically its maximum throughput.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] While the best case performance was less than Ethernet, the general case was equivalent and the worst case was dramatically better.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] An Ethernet network could collapse when too busy due to excessive collisions.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] An ARCNET would keep on going at normal (or even better) throughput.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Throughput on a multi-node collision-based Ethernet was limited to between 40% and 60% of bandwidth usage (depending on source).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Although 2.5 Mbit/s ARCNET could at one time outperform a 10 Mbit/s Ethernet in a busy office on slow processors, ARCNET ultimately gave way to Ethernet as improved processor speeds reduced the impact of collisions on overall throughput, and Ethernet costs dropped.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In the early 1980s, ARCNET was much cheaper than Ethernet, in particular for PCs.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] For example, in 1985 SMC sold ARCNET cards for around US$300 whilst an Ungermann-Bass Ethernet card plus transceiver could cost US$500.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Another significant difference is that ARCNET provides the sender with a definite success/failure status of delivery at the receiver before the token passes on to the next node.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This permits much faster fault recovery within the higher level protocols, rather than having to wait for a timeout on the expected replies.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] ARCNET also doesn't waste network time transmitting to a node not ready to receive the message, since the initial hardware-level inquiry establishes that the recipient is able and ready to receive the larger message before it is sent across the bus.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] One further advantage that ARCNET enjoyed over collision-based Ethernet is that it guarantees equitable access to the bus by everyone on the network.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Although it takes a time to get the token depending on the number of nodes and the size of the messages currently being sent, a node will always receive it within a predictable maximum time.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] This made ARCNET an ideal real-time networking system, which explains its use in the embedded systems and process control markets.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Token Ring has similar qualities, but is much more expensive to implement than ARCNET.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In spite of ARCNET's deterministic operation and historic suitability for real-time environments such as process control, the general availability of switched gigabit Ethernet and Quality of service capabilities in Ethernet switches has all but eliminated ARCNET today.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] At first the system was deployed using the RG-62/U coaxial cable commonly used in IBM mainframe environments to connect 3270 terminals and controllers, but later added support for twisted pair and fibre media.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] At ARCNET's lower speeds (2.5 Mbit/s), Cat-3 cable is good enough to run ARCNET.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] Some ARCNET twisted-pair products supported cable runs over 2,000 ft (610 m) on standard Cat-3 cable, far beyond anything Ethernet could do on any kind of copper cable.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] In the early 1990s, Thomas-Conrad Corporation developed a 100 Mbit/s topology called TCNS based on the ARCNET protocol, which also supported RG-62, twisted-pair, and fiber optic media.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] TCNS enjoyed some success until the availability of lower-cost 100 Mbit/s Ethernet put an end to the general deployment of ARCNET as a LAN protocol.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arcnet] However, because of its simple and robust nature, ARCNET controllers are still sold and used in industrial, embedded, and automotive applications.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:fire-alarm-control-panel/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
